{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1d15386-c077-47a7-a5e5-822c7da075a0","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET 8 CPU profiling. No install beyond the .NET SDK tools.\n\n### Setup (one-time)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### Collect a 30-second CPU trace\n```powershell\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect with the cpu-sampling profile\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper analysis)\nIf you need kernel-level detail (context switches, I/O, etc.):\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500 -KernelEvents:Profile -ClrEvents:Default\n```\n\nPerfView produces ETW traces with flame graphs and hot-path analysis — more powerful but steeper learning curve.\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for quick triage. Escalate to PerfView if you need OS-level context.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0752c611-1866-4e87-b85e-3ec76ecc2a95","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should give a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe best tool for this scenario is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU profiling specifically, `dotnet-trace` with the cpu-sampling profile is the simplest, but PerfView gives richer ETW-based data. Since they have admin access and it's Windows, PerfView is the gold standard for CPU analysis.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"680C:1025EC:ABC9C4D:BAC1C94:69FD3B8A"},"id":"504a40b1-55f9-4daf-8cac-659710656651","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:25:41.959Z","parentId":"96deec21-4a17-4eec-a2cb-e7d5863d1d69"}
